          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>On ultrasound, a fetus is found to have markedly reduced amniotic fluid (oligohydramnios). Which of the following is the most likely underlying mechanism?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Impaired secretion by the amniotic membrane</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The amniotic membrane contributes to early fluid production, but fetal urine becomes the dominant source. Oligohydramnios typically reflects a renal or urinary tract problem rather than a membrane secretion defect.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Decreased fetal urine output</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Amniotic fluid is primarily derived from fetal urine. Oligohydramnios usually indicates impaired renal function or urinary tract obstruction.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Excessive reabsorption by the chorion laeve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The chorion laeve is the smooth portion of the chorion whose villi have atrophied. It does not play a significant role in amniotic fluid regulation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Drainage through a patent urachus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A patent urachus (persistent allantois) causes urine leakage from the umbilicus after birth. It does not reduce amniotic fluid volume in utero.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Oligohydramnios usually reflects reduced fetal urine output. Severe oligohydramnios can impair lung development, producing the Potter sequence of pulmonary and limb abnormalities."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Oligohydramnios usually reflects decreased fetal urine output. Severe cases can lead to the Potter sequence — pulmonary hypoplasia and limb deformities due to fetal compression."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
