          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which of the following substances is able to cross the placental barrier from mo</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which of the following substances is able to cross the placental barrier from mother to fetus?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Heparin</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Heparin is a large, negatively charged molecule that does not cross the placental barrier. This property makes it the preferred anticoagulant during pregnancy.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Immunoglobulin M</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>IgM is a large pentameric antibody that cannot cross the placental barrier. Elevated IgM in a newborn suggests an active intrauterine infection rather than passive maternal transfer.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Immunoglobulin G</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. IgG crosses the placental barrier via receptor-mediated transport on the syncytiotrophoblast, providing the newborn with passive immunity for 3–6 months after birth.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Bacteria</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Bacteria generally cannot cross the intact placental barrier, unlike certain viruses such as rubella and cytomegalovirus which can cross and cause congenital infections.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "IgG is the only immunoglobulin class that crosses the placental barrier, providing the newborn with passive immunity for 3–6 months. Heparin and bacteria generally do not cross."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! IgG is selectively transported across the placental barrier, conferring passive immunity to the newborn. Heparin, IgM, and bacteria are generally blocked."
                }
              ],
